article.headline: Holdsclaw, battling hamstring injury, scores 11 in loss
article.linkText: Holdsclaw returns, but Monarchs still beat Mystics
article.story:
SACRAMENTO (AP) -- The Washington Mystics got unexpected good
news Wednesday night, learning that star Chamique Holdsclaw was
healthy enough to take on the Sacramento Monarchs.

It didn't matter. Forward Yolanda Griffith scored 20 points as
the Sacramento Monarchs downed the Washington Mystics 83-62 at Arco
Arena.

Three other Monarchs scored in double figures, as forward
Tangela Smith had 14, DeMya Walker had 10, and Ticha Penicheiro
added 10 points and five assists for the streaking Monarchs (7-8).

Sacramento has now won four of its last five games. It was
Sacramento's largest margin of victory this season.

"We're playing together, and we have a lot of chemistry,"
Monarchs coach Maura McHugh said. "We've got to get to .500 by the
all-star break."

Named as a reserve for the July 12 All-Star game in New York
City, Griffith had her way with the Mystics defense. She hit 6-of-9
field goals, and sank all eight of her free throw attempts.

The Monarchs used ball control and sharp shooting to get it
done. Sacramento had just one turnover until late in the first
half, and shot 52 percent (30-of-57) from the field.

Washington, which made the playoffs for the first time in
franchise history in 2002, has lost seven straight games and 10 of
its last 11.

The Mystics (2-10) were thrilled to have Holdsclaw, who was
expected to sit out her third straight game after re-injuring her
right hamstring against Cleveland June 20. She finished with 11
points, with just three coming in the second half.

Guard Coco Miller had 15 points for the Mystics. Washington shot
a paltry 35 percent (26-73).

"We're happy (Holdsclaw) is back, but she struggled tonight,"
Mystics coach Marianne Stanley said. "Her and a lot of other folks
struggled."

Up 40-29 at halftime, Sacramento used a 12-3 run to open the
second half to pull away. Walker hit a short jumper and Edna
Campbell nailed a three-pointer to open the half. After Holdsclaw's
three-pointer, Penicheiro and Smith helped Sacramento score seven
more and the rout was on.

Holdsclaw started strong, taking two rebounds away from Monarchs
in the first minute. With the 6-foot-4 Smith assigned to guard her,
Holdsclaw hit the game's first bucket on an eight-foot jumper. She
was 4-for-10 with eight points and four rebounds in the first half.

She faltered in the second half, hitting just one three-pointer.
The Monarchs took advantage when she was out. Up by seven points
already, the Monarchs extended their lead 27-15 with the Mystics'
star out as LaKeshia Frett scored five points on the 7-2 run.

Griffith dominated on the block, hitting four of her six shots
and earning as many free throws as the entire Mystics team (six).
The Mystics had trouble making shots (12-of-34), or getting free
ones.

Last in the league in free throw attempts with 157 entering the
game, Washington made its first trip to the line with 6:40 left in
first half when Nakia Sanford hit one of two attempts.

Despite missing their first six shots, the Monarchs never
trailed by more than two, then recovered to hit 13 of their next 20
field goals in the first half.
